    <p id='tribute-info'>Starlight came on a cold autumn day when he was found in the parking lot at work and my boss said I needed to take him home. At first he seemed like any other playful kitten. As he grew up I noticed his coat was very short, silky,and shiny and his build very muscular and extremely strong for his size. Starlight decided to work on a ceiling tile one day and came back to the same spot on every day and dug at the ceiling tile for 10 to 15 minutes a day for about 4 months until the celing tile came out. Shredded paneling in the living room. Put a mouse on top of keresene heater. About 6 months ago learned to open deadbolt, and since I don't want Starlight going outside I turned the deadbolt around key side in because he can't use a key. I now have to use a padlock to lock my house when I leave, but Starlight can't get out. There is a latch on my door also and when I'm near the door he likes to leap on my shoulder, purr and paw at the latch. Yesterday I reached into my jacket pocked and found a freshly killed mouse that my beautiful Burmese(mix?)cat decided must have been a good idea to put in there at some point since the last time I wore it. The entertainment never ends. I suggest for anyone who wants a Burmese cat that they own their own home and do not care if their Burmese climbs up door facings, pulls out insulation and makes 8 inch and getting bigger every day holes in paneling.They are adorable, loving companions, require very little grooming due to their short fur and get along well with other pets.</p>
